To further assess the relationship between the number of available variants and the robustness of RheoScale 2.0’s classifications, we used three HTP datasets for PLPro.  
For each position in a dataset, we randomly subsampled the set of 20 variants to generate datasets with 5-19 variants per position, with 10 random samples created for each variant number.  
(E.g., 10 randomly selected subsamples with 12 variants each).

For activity data, RheoScale analyses were carried out for each subsample, and assignment accuracies were calculated relative to assignments using all 20 variants, ten histogram bins, and default assignment thresholds as "truth".
In another implementation, RheoScale analyses of activity data were carried out using the default bin number and assessed relative to assginments using 10 bins as "truth" (as above).

Likewise, subsamples were creataed for HTP abundance and inhibitor datasets, RheoScale analyses were carried out for each subsample, 
and assignment accuracies were calculated relative to assignments using all 20 variants, the default number of histogram bins, and default assignment thresholds as "truth"

For each set of subsamples (e.g., ten replicates of random subsamples with 12 variants each), we then calculated the average accuracies and standard deviations.  
